  						<table align=center cellpadding='3' width='85%'>
  <tr><td class='spti2'>PLAYER JOURNAL</td></tr>  <tr><td class='db'><font class='dbti'>Kaesora and the Portal of Fear</font> - Etha Tanglewood</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'> </td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>Nina told Etha that someone was looking for very experienced adventurers to relieve Xalgoz of his fang, deep in the dungeon of Kaesora, so she teleported to the Dreadlands and ran to the elfin outpost of Firiona Vie.
<p>
There, she was the last and youngest member of the expedition which included the paladins Uzmeil and Izer, bard Fenril, and a cleric and a shaman whose names I can't recall. Everyone met at Karnor's for the teleport to the Emerald Jungle. I gathered the winds and they brought us to the jungle, where we were set upon by many things. Some we killed, finally we just rooted them and ran.
<p>
Up the giant stair, entering the Field of Bone, continuing on to Kaesora.
<p>
Several expeditions were making their own way to Xalgoz, who was undoubtedly trembling with fear. We followed a tattered and inaccurate map into a deep pit... atop a deeper pit... next to a Really Deep Pit... Now as we were descending, the paladins were fighting a battle to keep spiders from killing us all. Eventually they all ran away and the paladins followed us down.
<p>
I suggested, perhaps, camping so that the spiders would forget about us...
<p>
Well, they found us first, them and their twenty friends. The tanks taunted the spiders off me and I summoned the winds to bring us back to the jungle.
<p>
Can you believe they were going to go dungeon crawling without a druid? <i>Merde!</i>
<p>
Back we went at wolf speed. This time we turned the map around and ended up at the Library. A nice place (and I found a Kunzar Mantle on a tortured librarian), but... again not the place we were looking for.
<p>
We tried turning the map over, where all the dark marks were. Aha! We came to an ornate chapel, invisible to the undead who guarded it. Xalgoz stood there, leering at us. We gathered our mana and sharpened our weapons... when a Teir'Dal entered the chapel, glaring about at us. "May I help you?" she asked frostily.
<p>
Xalgoz turned at the noise and saw the shaman. He screamed in rage and sent in his pet skeleton, following behind. We sliced, diced, baked and shaked, and he was dead, Uzmeil holding a fang torn from the Sarnak's mouth.
<p>
Bhlit, the Teir'Dal brought in the rest of her group, and we stared at the mirror of our own group. It seems the person leading the last group in the chapel had told both our groups that it was free; we'd arrived first only because we had traveled invisibly. Fairness said that she would be able to kill Xalgoz should he unwisely return, and then we could follow. Bored with this scheme, the casters (aside from me) gated away. Not wanting to wait any more than the others, I ported the bard back to the Emerald Jungle, and then took the others to South Ro.
<p>
I asked why... and they said they were looking to join a raid on the lair of the dreaded Cazic-Thule, the plane of Fear. So I hopped Izer and I to Feerrott, Uzmeil having run out of range (and not being one to listen to a small druid such as I).
<p>
Uzmeil never made it to Feerrott and we never learned why. Izer asked if I'd ever seen the portal to Fear; I had the night before, as Nashuya and I helped Luladanielle recover the body she had left there. We set off anyway and fought spectre after spectre until we stood before the portal, a giant Gate filled with the shimmering forces that lay between our Material Plane and that of a God itself.
<p>
A necromancer guarded the gate but not for long. Some people, including paladin Toran and warrior Nasgul (whom I'd met in Karnor's one night) were gathered, hoping to be called to battle fiends in another plane of existence. Izer and I asked if our help would be needed, and were told to wait below. I'd never been beyond the one world we all know.
<p>
So we pulled spectre after spectre, for four hours we killed them until we were overburdened with loot. I brought us to Rivervale and Kaladim and back to Feerrott and its portal. We fought more; Torth sent word he was interested in killing spectres and so I asked him to come, but to beware of evil undead.
<p>
Torth died in desperate, heroic battle as he tried to find us. Izer revived him and we fought our way back to the portal. The paladin then received word that his skills were needed in the alter plane; but then spectres attacked, so I grabbed up Torth on wings of magic and we appeared elsewhere, while Izer ascended to battle the minions of Cazic-Thule.
<p>
I've still never seen the Planes... perhaps my sister Nina will be needed there, someday, and then she can tell me of them.
<p>
I sent word to my brother Dulcet that the time had come for him to continue his story; and camped.</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db2'><a href='view_profile.asp?Action=Journal&Id=22257'>Return to Etha's Journal</a></td></tr>
